Lancashire, named with Old Scandanavian <i>hryggr</i> ‘ridge’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’. Compare   Rigsby  ."]},{"name":"Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames","meanings":["English: variant of   Bulcock  .   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes that in the parish registers of Bolton by Bowland (WR Yorks) the same family name is spelled  <i>Bulcock</i>,  <i>Bowcocke</i>, and  <i>Boocock</i> (1608–30), and that Edward Bowcock of Howgill (WR Yorks) is also called Bulcock in a will dated 1677. Compare also Alice Bowcock, 1641, Chr. Bulcock, 1646 in   IGI   (Barnoldswick, WR Yorks)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":65,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be o